    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:d792a363-758f-4b41-a248-1230cdf91c9e",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 50-year-old male who works as a senior sales manager at a logistics company, spending much of his day behind a desk or traveling for client meetings. He is of medium build with a noticeably rounded abdomen — a physical tell-tale of years of sedentary living and business dinners. His complexion is slightly ruddy, and he carries a tired look around his eyes that betrays long working hours and disrupted sleep patterns. Despite being well-dressed and outwardly composed, he admits to feeling persistently fatigued and occasionally short of breath after climbing stairs.\n\n{patientName} is married with two teenage children, and he describes his home life as busy but fulfilling. Weekends are spent watching football matches, occasional golf rounds with colleagues, and large family meals. His diet is heavily weighted toward red meat, processed foods, and restaurant cuisine. He rarely cooks at home and frequently skips breakfast, instead relying on coffee and pastries. He smokes about 8–10 cigarettes per day and consumes alcohol socially — roughly 3–4 units several nights per week.\n\nHe first became aware of his elevated cholesterol during a routine company health check two years ago. At the time, he dismissed it as a minor concern, but a recent follow-up blood panel showed persistently elevated LDL and total cholesterol levels with borderline high triglycerides. His primary care physician referred him to a cardiometabolic clinic for further evaluation and management. He has no history of chest pain or prior cardiovascular events, but his sedentary lifestyle and family history raise significant concern.\n\n{patientName} is anxious about starting long-term medication and frequently asks about \"natural alternatives.\" He is open to lifestyle changes in principle but struggles with consistency. He acknowledges that his stress levels are high and that he uses food and alcohol as coping mechanisms. He recently joined a gym but has only attended twice in two months."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
